### FINDINGS
| Surfaced idea (CHANGELOG:line) | What it is | spec-kit equivalent or GAP (file:line) | Verdict | Net-new value |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Phase-0 classification was removed after recent classification/routing additions [SOURCE: external/gem-team-main/CHANGELOG.md:16] [SOURCE: external/gem-team-main/CHANGELOG.md:25] | Reversal signal: upfront task classification became redundant enough to simplify away. | Partial equivalent: spec-kit still classifies intent in Gate 1 and routes skills separately [SOURCE: AGENTS.md:189-200]; sk-code already delays intent classification until after surface selection [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-code/README.md:80-84]. | ADAPT | Add a “classification must control a real route” guard; avoid metadata-only upfront classifiers. |
| Research-findings YAML search at agent initialization [SOURCE: external/gem-team-main/CHANGELOG.md:236] | Agents search `research_findings_{focus_area}.yaml` during init, not just generic memory/context. | GAP/partial: @context reads continuity then memory/context broadly, but no focus-area research-findings lookup primitive [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/CONTEXT.md:160-171]. | ADAPT | Useful as a packet-local, focus-scoped retrieval hook before broad memory search. |
| High-confidence plan-template cache plus bypasses [SOURCE: external/gem-team-main/CHANGELOG.md:267] [SOURCE: external/gem-team-main/CHANGELOG.md:268] | Cache successful DAG/task/wave/contract plans by objective category, with explicit bypass for same-bug/template cases. | GAP: spec-kit has learning measurement and fan-out orchestration, but no reusable plan-template cache [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/feature_catalog/feature_catalog.md:888-922] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/SKILL.md:165-170]. | ADAPT | Candidate for proposal-only “similar packet plan skeletons,” with stale/bypass controls. |
| Shared-component pre-save check and failure-log reinjection [SOURCE: external/gem-team-main/CHANGELOG.md:571] | Before saving/redelegating, check shared-component impact and inject prior failure logs into repeated work. | Partial equivalent: spec-kit has `detect_changes` as read-only diff impact preflight [SOURCE: README.md:630-636], but not an automatic shared-component pre-save gate. | ADAPT | Tie impact checks to “shared/hot component changed” rather than relying on manual reviewer memory. |
| Accessibility tree snapshots over screenshots for reliability [SOURCE: external/gem-team-main/CHANGELOG.md:640] | Browser-testing gotcha: semantic/accessibility verification should prefer structured accessibility snapshots when screenshots are noisy. | Partial equivalent: sk-code verification still names browser screenshots as WEBFLOW evidence [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-code/README.md:86]; accessibility exists as a concern but not this reliability preference. | ADAPT | Add modality guidance: screenshots for visual layout, accessibility snapshots for semantic/a11y assertions. |
| `parallelizable` field added, then removed from task configuration [SOURCE: external/gem-team-main/CHANGELOG.md:590] [SOURCE: external/gem-team-main/CHANGELOG.md:691] | Reversal signal: per-task parallelizability flags did not survive; orchestration should infer/derive concurrency from dependencies/conflicts. | Equivalent stronger path: deep-loop fan-out uses concurrency-capped isolated lineages/status ledger instead of per-task booleans [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/SKILL.md:165-170]. | REJECT | Do not add `parallelizable` flags; prefer explicit dependency/conflict scopes plus runtime isolation. |

- [F-012-01] Most novel signal is the **classification rollback**: Gem Team recently added task classification/context-envelope routing, then removed Phase-0 task type classification [SOURCE: external/gem-team-main/CHANGELOG.md:16] [SOURCE: external/gem-team-main/CHANGELOG.md:25]. For spec-kit, this argues for a “classifier earns its keep” rule because current gates already classify intent and skill routing separately [SOURCE: AGENTS.md:189-200].
- [F-012-02] The **focus-area research findings lookup** is more specific than generic context-envelope work: Gem Team initialized agents by searching `research_findings_{focus_area}.yaml` [SOURCE: external/gem-team-main/CHANGELOG.md:236]. Spec-kit’s @context path is continuity-first and memory-backed, but does not show a focus-area research-file lookup before memory expansion [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/CONTEXT.md:160-171].
- [F-012-03] The **plan-template cache** is a fresh mechanism, not just “memory”: Gem Team cached high-confidence generated DAGs/contracts/assignments by objective category and added bypasses [SOURCE: external/gem-team-main/CHANGELOG.md:267] [SOURCE: external/gem-team-main/CHANGELOG.md:268]. Spec-kit should only adapt this as proposal-only plan skeleton recall, not automatic execution.
- [F-012-04] The **accessibility_snapshot over screenshots** item is a concrete browser-testing gotcha [SOURCE: external/gem-team-main/CHANGELOG.md:640]. It fills a small but real gap in spec-kit’s current screenshot-centered WEBFLOW evidence rule [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-code/README.md:86].
- [F-012-05] The `parallelizable` add/remove pair is a useful negative signal: Gem Team tried explicit task parallel flags and removed them [SOURCE: external/gem-team-main/CHANGELOG.md:590] [SOURCE: external/gem-team-main/CHANGELOG.md:691]. Spec-kit’s isolated fan-out/status-ledger design is the better equivalent [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/SKILL.md:165-170].

### NEGATIVE / RULED-OUT
- Context envelope, auto-skills, task classification, token efficiency, pre-mortem/resilience, and standard output contract were already dedicated earlier angles, so changelog hits in those buckets are mostly not net-new [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/007-gem-team-adoption-matrix/deep-research-strategy.md:35-43] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/007-gem-team-adoption-matrix/deep-research-strategy.md:77-84].
- Removing persistent memory is not worth adopting; spec-kit’s memory stack is central and already has preflight, dedup, quality scoring, learning history, and retrieval governance [SOURCE: external/gem-team-main/CHANGELOG.md:535] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/feature_catalog/feature_catalog.md:2772-2782].
- Strict JSON output/token-efficiency changes are covered by prior token-efficiency/standard-output work and by existing validation/token-budget gates [SOURCE: external/gem-team-main/CHANGELOG.md:448] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/feature_catalog/feature_catalog.md:4713-4719].
- Generic wave orchestration remains rejected as a new import because spec-kit deep-loop fan-out has stronger lineage isolation, salvage, and merge semantics [SOURCE: external/gem-team-main/CHANGELOG.md:557] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/SKILL.md:165-170].
- `get_errors` as first lightweight validation is directionally useful but already resembles spec-kit’s dry-run/preflight and two-stage validation patterns, so it is not a separate adoption candidate [SOURCE: external/gem-team-main/CHANGELOG.md:715] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/feature_catalog/feature_catalog.md:2772-2782] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-doc/references/global/validation.md:34-40].

### OPEN QUESTIONS
- Should focus-area research findings be a first-class @context lookup rule, or only a deep-research/deep-review loop convention?
- What qualifies a spec-kit plan as safe for plan-template reuse: same spec level, same stack, same file-surface, or evaluator score?
- Can accessibility snapshot support be standardized across our Chrome DevTools/bdg paths without making screenshots optional for visual regressions?

